Unifying the data based on the keys so I can just deal with a unique whole dataset.

Since we "can't" join the order products directly to not duplicates orders in the data, I will transform the order products data to have some new features unique by order id. For simplicity, I will consider an KG the same as an unity of the product.

In [7]:
#Since I want to have different columns for KG and UN products (maybe KG products takes longer to separate?), I will groupby 
#'buy_unit' aswell and then calculate the total by summing them.
orderproducts = order_products.groupby(['order_id', 'buy_unit'])\
                                      .agg({'product_id':'size', 
                                            'quantity':'sum' })\
                              .unstack()\
                              .reset_index()
#Renaming columns
orderproducts.columns = ['order_id','size_kg', 'size_un', 'quantity_kg', 'quantity_un']
#filling the NaNs with 0 which is the proper value for that case
orderproducts = orderproducts.fillna(0)
#calculating totals
orderproducts['total_size'] = orderproducts[['size_kg','size_un']].sum(axis=1)
orderproducts['total_quantity'] = orderproducts[['quantity_kg','quantity_un']].sum(axis=1)
In [8]:
#Merging all data into a single dataframe. The last merge is left-based to not delete any order from the data that doesn't

           .merge(store.rename(columns={'lat':'lat_store', 
                                        'lng':'lng_store'}), 
                  on= 'store_branch_id')\
           .merge(orderproducts, on='order_id', how = 'left')

#Transforming string date to datetime object
df['promised_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['promised_time'])

Feature Engineering¶

Having the data in a single DF, I will create some features before doing exploratory data analysis.\ The features that will be created below are:

  • Distance between store branch and delivery address (I will use geodesic distance to not have to deal with google maps API for route distance here)
  • Day of week of promised time
  • Hour of the day of promised time
  • If promised time is rush hour
  • Number of total (size) products * found rate of shopper
  • Total_quantity_products/picking speed
  • If the store is in the 10% more popular stores (by number of orders)
  • Proportion of orders for that store branch
  • Number of orders the shopper were responsible that day
  • Average time between shopper orders during the day
  • Average time between branch orders during the day
  • Daily Cyclical from promised time

Distance¶

In [10]:
#Defining a function to transform the data
def calc_distance(df):
    df['coord_1'] = list(zip(df['lat'], df['lng']))
    df['coord_2'] = list(zip(df['lat_store'], df['lng_store']))
    df['distance'] = df[['coord_1', 'coord_2']].apply(lambda x: distance(x['coord_1'], 
                                                                         x['coord_2']).km, 
                                                      axis =1)
    return df['distance']

#Adding the distane column to the data
df['distance'] = calc_distance(df)

Day of week, hour of the day and if it is rush hour¶

I will be considering rush hour as hours belonging to lunch time (11,12,13) and end of workday (18/19/20)\

In [11]:
def day_of_week(df):
    df['day_of_week'] = df['promised_time'].apply(lambda x: x.day_name())
    df['hour_of_day'] = df['promised_time'].apply(lambda x: x.hour)
    df['rush_hour'] = np.where(df['hour_of_day'].isin([11,12,13,18,19,20]),1,0)
    return df[['day_of_week', 'hour_of_day', 'rush_hour']]

df[['day_of_week', 'hour_of_day', 'rush_hour']] = day_of_week(df)

I will be using total (size) products requested to that since the found_rate seems to be related to a unique product in a shelf, and not its available quantity

def total_products_found(df):
    df['total_products_found'] = df['total_size']*df['found_rate']
    return df

Store is in 10% more popular¶

In [14]:
def popular_store(df, percentil):
    #getting total numbers of stores to be tagged based on the percentage
    number_stores = int(len(df['store_id'].unique())*percentil)
    #filtering op stores
    top_stores = df.groupby('store_id').size().sort_values(ascending=False)[:number_stores].index
    #tagging if the store is popular
    df['top_store'] = np.where(df['store_id'].isin(top_stores), 1, 0)
    return df

df = popular_store(df, 0.1)

Proportion of orders for that branch related to its store¶

In [15]:
def branch_proportion(df):
    #calculating totals by branch and by store
    storebranch = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby('store_branch_id').size(), columns=['t_branch']).reset_index()
    store = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby('store_id').size(), columns=['t_store']).reset_index()
    #joining them in DF
    df = df.merge(storebranch, on='store_branch_id' )\
           .merge(store, on='store_id')
    #proportion
    df['branch_proportion'] = df['t_branch']/df['t_store']
    
    return df['branch_proportion']

df['branch_proportion'] = branch_proportion(df)

Number of orders the shopper made that day¶

In [16]:
def total_shopper_order(df):
    df['date'] = df['promised_time'].dt.date
    total_shopper = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby(['shopper_id','date']).size(), 
                                 columns=['total_shopper_day']).reset_index()
    df = df.merge(total_shopper, on=['shopper_id', 'date'])
    return df['total_shopper_day']

df['total_shopper_day'] = total_shopper_order(df)

Average hours between shopper orders¶

In [17]:
def avg_hour_order(df, col):
    #sorting by col and datetime order 
    df = df.sort_values([col, 'promised_time'])
    #getting the values from row below
    df[['col_after', 'promised_time_after']] = df[[col, 'promised_time']].shift(-1)
    #filtering data for only rows with same col value and same day
    a = df[(df[col]==df['col_after']) & \
           (df['promised_time_after'].dt.date==df['promised_time'].dt.date)]
    #calculating difference in hours
    a['avg_hour'] = (a['promised_time_after'] - a['promised_time'])/np.timedelta64(1, 'h')
    a = a.groupby(col).agg({'avg_hour':'mean'}).reset_index()
    
    #joining with original df
    df = df.merge(a, on=col, how='left')
    return df['avg_hour']

df['avg_hour_shopper_order'] = avg_hour_order(df, 'shopper_id')

Cyclical variable from promised time¶

In [19]:
#Max values to a day in seconds in 24hours*3600 seconds

def cyclical_time(df):
    # Transforming promised time to total seconds of the day
    df['t_seconds'] = df['promised_time'].dt.hour*3600 + df['promised_time'].dt.minute*60 + df['promised_time'].dt.second
    df['sin_time'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * df['t_seconds']/(24*3600))
    df['cos_time'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * df['t_seconds']/(24*3600))
    return df[['sin_time', 'cos_time']]

df[['sin_time', 'cos_time']] = cyclical_time(df)

def plot_cat(df, col1, col2 = 'total_minutes'):
    """
    Function defined to plot caregorical variables to be related to the target
    Param:
    df: DataFrame
    col1, col2: column in DF
    """
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9,6))
    sns.histplot(data=df, x=col2, hue = col1, ax=ax)
    ax.set_title(f"Histogram of total_minutes by {col1}")
    ax.figure
    
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9,6))
    sns.boxplot(data=df, y=col2, x = col1, ax=ax)
    ax.set_title(f"Box PLot of total_minutes by {col1}")
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha='right')
    ax.figure
    
def plot_numeric(df, col1, col2 = 'total_minutes', hue = None, kind = 'scatter', xlim = None):
    """
    Function defined to plot numerical variables to be related to the target
    Param:
    df: DataFrame
    col1, col2: column in DF
    """
    #plotting only 0.05 to 0.95 centile to rmeove "outliers" in graphs to better visualizations
    g = sns.jointplot(data=df, x=col1, y=col2, hue = hue, kind = kind, height=8, ratio=2, 
                      xlim=xlim)

Modelling¶

I will define here the code to code properly encode the variables and create a model

In [48]:
#Defining numeric transformer to fill NaNs with median and MinMaxScaling values to range (0,1)
num_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[("num_imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="median")), 
                                      ("scaler", MinMaxScaler())])

#Defining categorical transformer
cat_transformer = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore")

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(transformers=[("num", num_transformer, num_feats),
                                               ("cat", cat_transformer, onehot_feats)],
                                remainder='passthrough')

def model(x, y, preprocess_object, model, parameters_to_try=None):
    """
    Function to define a complete model with a preprocessor, a regression model and parameters to try
    Params:
    x: Features
    y: Target
    preprocess_object: ColumnTransformer object with desired transformations
    model: any model from sklearn
    parameters_to_try: dict like parameters dictionary to be used in a RandomizedSearch
    """

    #appending model to preprocess transformer.
    model_pipe = Pipeline(steps=[("transformer", preprocess_object), 
                            ("regressor", model)])
    
    #getting training and test dataset
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
    
    
    #Defining the model if randomized search
    if parameters_to_try:
        randomsearch = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=model_pipe,
                                          param_distributions=parameters_to_try,
                                          n_iter = 50,
                                          n_jobs=-1,
                                          cv = 10,
                                          random_state=42                                   
                                          )
        #fitting data
        randomsearch.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
        return randomsearch, X_test, y_test
    
    #model without parameters
    else:
        model_pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)
        return model_pipe, X_test, y_test
